### The Rise of Granularity in Computing  
When **computer science** started to take shape, the idea of breaking data into **bits** and **bytes** was revolutionary.  Early **algorithms** were coarse: they processed whole numbers or simple strings.  As hardware grew more powerful, engineers began to crave *more detail*—hence the birth of **fine‑grained parallelism** in **multithreading** and **SIMD** (Single Instruction, Multiple Data) architectures.  The **fine‑grained** approach promised better **load balancing** and *the illusion* of efficiency, even when the overhead of spawning thousands of tiny tasks eclipsed any speed‑up.  

